{{Infobox ancient site |name = Kfar Tebnit |native_name = كفر تبنيت <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English --> | native_name_lang = ara<!-- ISO 639-2 code: "fr" for French, "ara" for Arabic --> |alternate_name = Kfar Tebnit |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = | grid_position = 128/157 L |map_size = |location = {{convert|4|km|mi}} south southeast of [[Nabatieh]], {{convert|37|km|mi}} southeast of [[Sidon]], [[Lebanon]] |region = |coordinates = {{coord|33|21|11|N|35|30|48|E|display=inline}} |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Heavy Neolithic]], [[Trihedral Neolithic]], [[Neolithic]] |cultures = [[Qaraoun culture]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = 1926 |archaeologists = [[E. Passemard]] |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = Unknown |website = |notes = }} '''Kfar Tebnit''' or '''Kfar Tibnit''' ({{lang-ar|كفر تبنيت}}) is a village located approximately {{convert|4|km|mi}} south southeast of [[Nabatieh]], {{convert|37|km|mi}} southeast of [[Sidon]] in [[Lebanon]].
Kfar Tebnit takes its name from [[Tabnith]] ([[Hebrew]] "Tibni"), a ruler in the area ca. 280 BC and known as the "king of two Sidons". The [[Eshmunazar II sarcophagus|sarcophagus of his son Eshmun-'azar]] was found to bear a long inscription aimed to prevent looting with assurances that the tomb contained no treasure.<ref name="Hitti2004">Hitti, 2004, p. 125</ref>
==Archaeology== A [[Heavy Neolithic]] archaeological site of the [[Qaraoun culture]] was discovered here in 1926 by E. Passemard. Heavy Neolithic materials were found alongside one [[Trihedral Neolithic]] along with more regular [[Neolithic]] pieces. The tools were in sharp condition, made of fresh chert or grey-green flint and are stored in the [[National Museum of Beirut]].<ref name="CopelandWescombe1966">Copeland and Wescombe, 1966, pp. 35-36</ref> ==History== In 1875 [[Victor Guérin]] visited, and found here 130 [[Metualis]].<ref>Guérin, 1880, p. [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr00gugoog#page/n561/mode/1up 521]</ref> ==References== {{reflist|25em}} ==Bibliography== {{refbegin}} *{{cite book|author1=L. Copeland|author2=P. Wescombe|title=Inventory of Stone-Age Sites in Lebanon: North, South and East-Central Lebanon, pp. 35-36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qhPRQwAACAAJ|accessdate=29 August 2011|year=1966|publisher=Impr. Catholique}} *{{cite book|last=Guérin|first=Victor|authorlink=Victor Guérin|title=Description Géographique Historique et Archéologique de la Palestine|url=https://archive.org/details/descriptiongogr00gugoog|volume=3: Galilee, pt. 2|year=1880|publisher= L'Imprimerie Nationale|location=Paris|language=French}} *{{cite book|first=Philip K|last= Hitti |authorlink=Philip Khuri Hitti | title=History of Syria, Including Lebanon and Palestine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=91YymsCw5DIC&pg=PA125|accessdate=4 January 2012|date=30 January 2004|publisher=Gorgias Press LLC|isbn=978-1-59333-119-1|pages=125–}} {{refend}} ==External links== *[http://www.localiban.org/article4444.html Kfar Tibnit], Localiban {{Nabatieh District}} {{Heavy Neolithic sites}} {{Archaeological sites in Lebanon}} {{Portal|Lebanon|Archaeology|Ancient Near East}} [[Category:Populated places in Nabatieh Governorate]] [[Category:Populated places in Lebanon]] [[Category:Heavy Neolithic sites]] [[Category:Trihedral Neolithic sites]] [[Category:Neolithic settlements]] [[C