[[File:Baalbek shaft.jpg|thumb|A star shaft in [[Baalbek]].]] '''Star shafts''' are narrow ducts leading out of ancient structures such as the [[Egyptian pyramids]] and [[Baalbek]]. The shafts start inside the [[Kings Chamber]] of the [[Great Pyramid of Giza]], and exit at the same height. Alexandre M. Badawy suggested that the shafts pointed to [[Orion's Belt]] during the period of the construction of the Giza complex.<ref name="Hockey2011">{{cite book|author=Thomas Hockey|title=How We See the Sky: A Naked-Eye Tour of Day and Night|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=df-4_iZbMl0C&pg=PA36|accessdate=30 April 2013|date=12 September 2011|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-34578-9|pages=36–}}</ref> It is thought that these openings were perhaps "air vents" for [[mummies]] or built to point to certain stars at the date of the [[pyramid]]s construction.<ref name="Information1980">{{cite book|author=Reed Business Information|title=New Scientist|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eXX8XvrbWlcC&pg=PA27|accessdate=30 April 2013|date=3 January 1980|publisher=Reed Business Information|pages=27–|issn=0262-4079}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=ACSM Bulletin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0_BOAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2013|year=2007|publisher=American Congress on Surveying and Mapping}}</ref><ref name="Hockey2011"/>
